&gt;&gt;Sheena Matheiken: So I wanna tell you a
little story about a little black dress and

00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:47.059
where it all started and how it started. And
not unlike a lot of creative endeavors, this

00:00:47.059 --> 00:00:56.079
project, dubbed "The Uniform Project" also
started in a place of dissatisfaction, deep

00:00:56.079 --> 00:01:05.790
seated dissatisfaction mainly from being in
a career that you're unhappy with, that has

00:01:05.790 --> 00:01:08.439
let, oop, sorry. I have something on my screen,
sorry.

00:01:08.439 --> 00:01:15.000
Mainly dissatisfaction with a lot of things,
a certain apathy, creative stagnation.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:21.900
I worked in advertising for a long time and
I had sort of hit a point of complete creative

00:01:21.900 --> 00:01:27.869
death as you call it, and wanted to sort of
step out of that and do something different

00:01:27.869 --> 00:01:33.490
and also something a little bit more consequential,
but didn't really know how to go about it.

00:01:33.490 --> 00:01:40.560
So started thinking about this and tried to
figure out what am I really learning from

00:01:40.560 --> 00:01:45.619
the industry I was in. And probably one of
the best lessons I learned which was very

00:01:45.619 --> 00:01:51.840
well captured by Hugh MacLeod was that if
you, as you can see, if you talk to people

00:01:51.840 --> 00:01:54.310
the way advertising talked to people, you
will get punched in the face.

00:01:54.310 --> 00:02:02.219
So what do you do with the skill sets I had
and how could I turn it around and stop manipulating

00:02:02.219 --> 00:02:07.450
people into buying things that they didn't
want or didn't need and instead use it for

00:02:07.450 --> 00:02:12.060
something a little bit more meaningful for
me? [clears throat] And that's where it began.

00:02:12.060 --> 00:02:23.790
So I started looking at the whole notion of
charity which I found really problematic because

00:02:23.790 --> 00:02:29.489
there was something wrong with the models
of philanthropy. I felt that it was a very

00:02:29.489 --> 00:02:37.819
paternalistic, patronizing approach to the
notion of giving which Oscar Wilde actually

00:02:37.819 --> 00:02:43.190
speaks about it very eloquently. "It is much
easier to have sympathy with suffering than

00:02:43.190 --> 00:02:44.890
it is to have sympathy with thought."

00:02:44.890 --> 00:02:50.310
And this really struck a chord because it
really, I found it really, really relevant

00:02:50.310 --> 00:02:56.319
in today's context because now we're in a
time where, because of the Web, everyone's

00:02:56.319 --> 00:03:01.890
a lot more aware of social issues and there's
definitely, there's a ground swell of wanting

00:03:01.890 --> 00:03:07.410
to do something about it and people sort of
coming together and there's a lot of trends

00:03:07.410 --> 00:03:12.959
happening in digital philanthropy. And there's
what we call the clicktivism culture which

00:03:12.959 --> 00:03:21.470
sort of in itself is problematic because it
is, it had sort of replaced an easy way to

00:03:21.470 --> 00:03:25.400
like sort of absolve yourself by, "Okay, I'll
make a quick donation here, quick donation

00:03:25.400 --> 00:03:30.489
there. It's all done." And it was, it didn't
really get to the root of the problem which

00:03:30.489 --> 00:03:35.659
was that it was impersonal, like there was
no real connection to what you were giving

00:03:35.659 --> 00:03:38.760
to or where it was going, none of that really
existed.

00:03:38.760 --> 00:03:45.080
So this whole model of giving that I found
really problematic because it was again this

00:03:45.080 --> 00:03:54.530
top down, the privileged giving to the underprivileged.
And it just doesn't seem right in this day

00:03:54.530 --> 00:03:59.110
and age because we were so much more connected
today and there is no us and them -- it's

00:03:59.110 --> 00:04:01.970
more us, a lot of us.

00:04:01.970 --> 00:04:07.240
So it was more about creating a sharing model
where the grounds for the, it was an even

00:04:07.240 --> 00:04:12.380
playing ground and it was more of whatever
it is, whether it was an idea, it was a concept,

00:04:12.380 --> 00:04:16.900
it was a cause, it was a philosophy. It was
more about sharing it than sort of dictating

00:04:16.900 --> 00:04:22.820
it or handing it down. And so these were the
ideas I had floating around in my head. Obviously

00:04:22.820 --> 00:04:27.490
not as well articulated. This is in hindsight
looking and kind of making sense of where

00:04:27.490 --> 00:04:30.080
it all came from.

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:34.330
So then I started thinking about, "Okay how
do I do this?" But the main issue I had with

00:04:34.330 --> 00:04:42.310
charity also was that it was so serious, everyone
approached it, it was somber, there was weight

00:04:42.310 --> 00:04:46.870
to it, that you were doing something good.
And did it have to be that way? Why couldn't

00:04:46.870 --> 00:04:51.970
it be fun? Why couldn't it be just something
people get excited about? And that's where

00:04:51.970 --> 00:04:58.460
I started thinking about a medium that I found
fun, which was fashion.

00:04:58.460 --> 00:05:04.460
But you start thinking about fashion and you
realize, okay, this is a hugely problematic

00:05:04.460 --> 00:05:11.860
field, a hugely problematic industry. And
I'm taking a quote slightly out of context

00:05:11.860 --> 00:05:17.430
but it still really applies: Marcel Duchamp
said, "Living is more of a question of what

00:05:17.430 --> 00:05:25.050
one spends than what one makes." And we have
become, it's so true because we are today

00:05:25.050 --> 00:05:33.419
a culture that is defined by what we consume
not by what we create. So fashion by definition

00:05:33.419 --> 00:05:40.460
is a toxic industry, probably the most toxic
in terms of the landfill it creates and the

00:05:40.460 --> 00:05:41.460
overconsumption.

00:05:41.460 --> 00:05:45.910
But I was really more interested in fashion
from one of its core values which was really

00:05:45.910 --> 00:05:57.699
about self expression. And I do think that
there is, it is probably the most approachable,

00:05:57.699 --> 00:06:03.509
most accessible and radically democratic form
of self expression, fashion, which is accessible

00:06:03.509 --> 00:06:08.240
to anybody, everyone does it, it's part of
your daily routine. So that's where it struck

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:12.169
a chord. I'm like, "Okay, I'm gonna use a
daily routine. Take this act of dressing up

00:06:12.169 --> 00:06:15.840
every day and do something fun with it."

00:06:15.840 --> 00:06:20.620
And that's sort of how it all started. So
I decided to give myself a creative challenge.

00:06:20.620 --> 00:06:26.160
And I said, "Alright I'm gonna challenge myself
to wear the same little black dress every

00:06:26.160 --> 00:06:33.410
day for 365 days." And I would reinvent it
every day, make it look different without

00:06:33.410 --> 00:06:39.620
buying anything new. So I was only allowed
to accessorize with found things, pre-owned,

00:06:39.620 --> 00:06:46.710
donated, thrifted, vintage, all those categories.
These were all pre-defined.

00:06:46.710 --> 00:06:53.961
And I designed the whole challenge to become
a fund raiser for a foundation called The

00:06:53.961 --> 00:06:58.819
Akanksha Foundation which is based in India
and they support education for underprivileged

00:06:58.819 --> 00:07:00.699
children in India.

00:07:00.699 --> 00:07:05.300
And this is a foundation I knew about through
a friend of mine and they have an incredibly

00:07:05.300 --> 00:07:10.820
progressive education model. They proved to
the government that it is not a money issue

00:07:10.820 --> 00:07:16.449
necessarily. They'd spend exact amount that
the Indian government spends in a public school

00:07:16.449 --> 00:07:22.020
on a child, and they use the same amount of
money to create a completely different education

00:07:22.020 --> 00:07:27.610
model to show that it's really -- the challenges
of education isn't just a money issue it's

00:07:27.610 --> 00:07:33.800
about the methods you teach and it's a question
of resources, [clears throat]. Excuse me.

00:07:33.800 --> 00:07:40.199
So they've proven to be incredibly successful
in 20 years and now have developed their own

00:07:40.199 --> 00:07:45.099
curriculum, are building their own schools.
So it's a great progressive, wonderfully,

00:07:45.099 --> 00:07:49.050
enabling initiative which is why I chose to
support Akanksha.

00:07:49.050 --> 00:07:55.970
So that was the set up, and then I started
in May 2009 was the beginning of the project

