00:12:17.350 --> 00:12:24.380
&gt;&gt;Sheena Matheiken: So how did we do this?

00:12:24.380 --> 00:12:31.920
It was all set up pretty straight forward.
We designed a website. I would post pictures

00:12:31.920 --> 00:12:38.470
everyday of the dailies, and you could donate
through PayPal directly to the cause. You

00:12:38.470 --> 00:12:44.260
could comment -- we created all these fun
tags to comment. You could tag them "baddie",

00:12:44.260 --> 00:12:49.160
"brave", "cute", "ugly", "try harder", or
make up your own tags which became incredibly

00:12:49.160 --> 00:12:54.149
popular with the community of followers because
people got very excited about comin' up with

00:12:54.149 --> 00:13:01.560
their own sort of pop culture references,
very interesting things in ways, sorry excuse

00:13:01.560 --> 00:13:08.610
me, to define the outfits. So it was actually
really fun.

00:13:08.610 --> 00:13:13.910
And all I did really was to start blogging
about it and Tweeted it every day, Facebooked

00:13:13.910 --> 00:13:18.670
it every day. Friends picked it up. Soon blogs
picked it up, and it completely became viral.

00:13:18.670 --> 00:13:24.350
And people started writing about it and then
the press picked it up and we didn't do any

00:13:24.350 --> 00:13:29.490
PR or anything. It was just purely viral,
purely through bloggers who found it interesting.

00:13:29.490 --> 00:13:36.889
And that's how it picked up. And by the end
of the project, we had raised over $100,000

00:13:36.889 --> 00:13:41.709
for Akanksha which put over 300 kids in school.

00:13:41.709 --> 00:13:50.100
And the other part of this whole exercise
was the dress itself which there was huge

00:13:50.100 --> 00:13:56.270
demand by the end of this. In the course of
the project people kept asking us, excuse

00:13:56.270 --> 00:13:58.600
me, "Are you gonna make the dress? Are you
gonna produce the dress?" So there was a lot

00:13:58.600 --> 00:14:06.800
of, it was a very interesting dilemma for
me because the whole purpose of this project

00:14:06.800 --> 00:14:12.670
was to, one side of it was to sort of make
a statement about overconsumption. So to be

00:14:12.670 --> 00:14:21.040
faced with this new sort of demand for a product
that we had created inadvertently was interesting.

00:14:21.040 --> 00:14:26.540
And so through the course of the project,
a few people had come together to help me

00:14:26.540 --> 00:14:31.709
and we had sort of really become the team,
The Uniform Project Team. And we really started

00:14:31.709 --> 00:14:37.140
thinking about, "What does that mean? Like
do we produce? Do we actually produce a product

00:14:37.140 --> 00:14:38.610
and put this out?"

00:14:38.610 --> 00:14:43.399
And we put a lot of thought into it and we
recognized that it was a very meaningful thing

00:14:43.399 --> 00:14:50.610
to do to actually create a limited edition
set of dresses which we produced and we put

00:14:50.610 --> 00:14:55.110
it out and a portion of it also went to the
fund raiser. So it helped us raise more money

00:14:55.110 --> 00:15:03.540
and it sold out really, really quickly. And
we also got hundreds and hundreds of accessory

00:15:03.540 --> 00:15:11.519
donations from all over the world. Which initially
I had put up this link almost as a joke as

00:15:11.519 --> 00:15:17.120
part of the site on top of you'll see there's
a little "Donate Accessories" button, which

00:15:17.120 --> 00:15:23.850
was really to encourage my friends to give
me shit to wear. Oops I just cursed. So because

00:15:23.850 --> 00:15:28.839
I knew I couldn't get through the whole year
with just the stuff in my wardrobe.

00:15:28.839 --> 00:15:35.990
But it turned out that I was speaking to a
lot more people than just my friends and my

00:15:35.990 --> 00:15:41.589
inbox was bombarded with people wanting to
send us stuff to wear, for me to wear. So

00:15:41.589 --> 00:15:46.500
we had to go through and pick a lot of stuff
out and carefully curate it because the whole

00:15:46.500 --> 00:15:49.870
purpose of this was not to accumulate more
stuff.

00:15:49.870 --> 00:15:54.930
So what we did at the end of the year was
auction off all those donated accessories

00:15:54.930 --> 00:15:59.699
and that money went to the foundation as well
which again got snatched up by the community

00:15:59.699 --> 00:16:05.740
which was fantastic. And got over two million
hits over the course of the first year and

00:16:05.740 --> 00:16:11.100
now we have a great following online that
continues [clears throat] to follow us.

00:16:11.100 --> 00:16:21.720
So by May 2010, last year which is when I
finished the project, this was the big gaping

00:16:21.720 --> 00:16:27.740
question -- what do you do now? What do I
do with this? We had inadvertently created

00:16:27.740 --> 00:16:34.339
this sort of a movement almost, but a brand
that people sort of associated with. We had

00:16:34.339 --> 00:16:39.380
made product so there was potential for this
to become a business, but we didn't wanna

00:16:39.380 --> 00:16:44.440
really lose the integrity of why this was
successful. And we were really trying to put

00:16:44.440 --> 00:16:49.420
a lot of rigor into thinking about what we
were as a brand and what it meant.

00:16:49.420 --> 00:16:55.040
And I'd be really wary to stand here and tell
you the recipe for success and why this worked

00:16:55.040 --> 00:16:59.410
because I don't think we really know hundred
percent. I think the minute you figure it

00:16:59.410 --> 00:17:06.920
out, you kinda lose the fun of it. And I think
but there are to quote Idris Mootee who the

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:15.589
founder of Idea Couture who is a pretty incredible
expert on branding and branding strategy.

00:17:15.589 --> 00:17:20.180
He says that, "brand is more than the sum
of its parts." And there's so much truth to

00:17:20.180 --> 00:17:28.339
it in that you can't really -- you can identify
the components but when you add it all up,

00:17:28.339 --> 00:17:33.600
it doesn't necessarily have to work. So there's
something much bigger than the sum of its

00:17:33.600 --> 00:17:34.760
parts that go into these things.

00:17:34.760 --> 00:17:40.510
So for us it was more about identifying what
those things were but also to identify what

00:17:40.510 --> 00:17:46.840
are the things that we had most fun with and
why was it fun for people. And what were the

00:17:46.840 --> 00:17:53.660
values that made it what it was? And so we
identified a bunch of things that it was about

00:17:53.660 --> 00:17:59.560
really and that made it, the values that really
made it sticky and fun for people and that's

00:17:59.560 --> 00:18:03.850
sort of where we started thinking about what
do we do next.

00:18:03.850 --> 00:18:09.429
And when I think about The Uniform Project
or what it was, and we've asked a lot of people,

00:18:09.429 --> 00:18:14.380
these are things that came to us, like this
is the stuff that our community told us. It's

00:18:14.380 --> 00:18:19.179
visual, it's viral, it's personal, it's accessible,
it's participatory, it's simple, it's social,

00:18:19.179 --> 00:18:21.070
it's addictive.

00:18:21.070 --> 00:18:27.400
So from there we decided let's not reinvent
anything, let's do what we're doing and take

00:18:27.400 --> 00:18:32.430
what I did and ask other people to do it.
So why not open it up, open up the platform,

00:18:32.430 --> 00:18:37.090
have more women do this because we kept getting
requests for people wanting to do it. And

00:18:37.090 --> 00:18:41.630
but how to you curate it because it's not
just about anyone being able to do it. How

00:18:41.630 --> 00:18:43.299
do you still keep it interesting?

00:18:43.299 --> 00:18:51.309
So we launched our second year early, sorry,
late last year as called "The Pilot Series"

00:18:51.309 --> 00:18:56.780
where we have now one woman taking on the
challenge for one month and they pick the

00:18:56.780 --> 00:19:02.039
cause and we work with them on the dress design.
It's still the little black dress.

00:19:02.039 --> 00:19:07.789
The idea of the black dress is so integral
to this whole theme because for us, from a

00:19:07.789 --> 00:19:14.720
fashion standpoint, it is such an iconic fashion
staple. It is at the center of most -- a lot

00:19:14.720 --> 00:19:19.340
of women in their wardrobes have a little
black dress. It is the perfect jumping board

00:19:19.340 --> 00:19:25.600
to build off of. So that is the idea and the
whole exercise is really about the art of

00:19:25.600 --> 00:19:29.250
accessorizing and doing it responsibly and
smartly and creatively.

00:19:29.250 --> 00:19:33.260
So this is the challenge. Now we have different
women taking on the challenge every month.

00:19:33.260 --> 00:19:40.169
We release the dresses every month as well.
And we have -- every month there's a new face

00:19:40.169 --> 00:19:46.150
on the site and it keeps growing. We have
a few -- we're looking into scaling this even

00:19:46.150 --> 00:19:49.560
further and we have a few other things we're
working on as well currently.

00:19:49.560 --> 00:19:57.750
So the real journey for us is really just
getting started. And it's really an evolution

00:19:57.750 --> 00:20:02.820
and it's an exploration right now of where
we could go and that's really the most exciting

00:20:02.820 --> 00:20:07.620
part that's come out of this for me personally
is that it has actually led me here to be

00:20:07.620 --> 00:20:13.030
able to leave what I used to do before I quit
my job, and now I'm doing this full time which

00:20:13.030 --> 00:20:14.030
is amazing.

00:20:14.030 --> 00:20:17.350
And I have this incredible team that's come
together and we've formed a business and it's

00:20:17.350 --> 00:20:23.010
got a really strong social component to it.
We're really strong on our philosophy about

00:20:23.010 --> 00:20:27.570
maintaining that social innovation side, the
social responsibility side, and continuing

00:20:27.570 --> 00:20:32.010
to do something that remains fun at its core.

00:20:32.010 --> 00:20:39.300
So that's really where we are. And I, again
I'm quoting Idris Mootee again but this is

00:20:39.300 --> 00:20:46.679
just such a great slide that I totally stole
it from one of his presentations. It's really

00:20:46.679 --> 00:20:53.120
the most important thing is those three dots
'cause a story has to evolve, it has to continue,

00:20:53.120 --> 00:20:58.720
and it has to grow whether it's a brand or
a business or a philosophy or an idea. It

00:20:58.720 --> 00:21:03.559
has to keep growing. So like that's the most
exciting part of all this for us and that's

00:21:03.559 --> 00:21:08.240
where we are.

