00:22:05.620 --> 00:22:25.980
&gt;&gt;female #2: Can you talk more about the sustainability
aspect 'cause it was obvious to me that it

00:22:25.980 --> 00:22:27.580
was a project to show what sustainability
could be versus what I think most people think

00:22:27.580 --> 00:22:28.580
it is?

00:22:28.580 --> 00:22:32.841
&gt;&gt;Sheena Matheiken: Right. That's a very interesting
question. I think when I started this, I was

00:22:32.841 --> 00:22:41.360
very, very conscious of the existence of the
eco-movement. I wouldn't necessarily say I

00:22:41.360 --> 00:22:45.471
was part of it. I mean I wasn't really part
of the fashion industry at all so for me it

00:22:45.471 --> 00:22:50.820
was a very personal thing. But I was already
in the habit of shopping vintage and I shop

00:22:50.820 --> 00:22:55.530
at thrift stores and vintage, and so it was
a natural sort of progression of, extension

00:22:55.530 --> 00:22:57.380
of what I was doing.

00:22:57.380 --> 00:23:04.049
But what I learned through the year was that
there was this really substantial movement

00:23:04.049 --> 00:23:11.440
happening. And in the course of the first
year, a lot of ethical designers and sustainable

00:23:11.440 --> 00:23:17.340
designers came to us 'cause they found it
really, they were excited about what we were

00:23:17.340 --> 00:23:23.090
doing because there's -- the people who are
at the front lines, the creative folk at the

00:23:23.090 --> 00:23:30.010
front lines of that movement, there was almost
a dissatisfaction on their end to not be just

00:23:30.010 --> 00:23:35.540
labeled as "eco" because there was a stigma
attached to that movement because it was labeled

00:23:35.540 --> 00:23:42.190
as Birkenstocks, granola, fashion which just
wasn't inspiring. And which is why mainstream

00:23:42.190 --> 00:23:44.250
wasn't accepting it as a movement.

00:23:44.250 --> 00:23:49.750
So I think the more creative, ethical designers
were really about keep it creative, keep it

00:23:49.750 --> 00:23:55.780
inspiring 'cause at the core of fashion for
women is desire. You wanna walk into a store

00:23:55.780 --> 00:24:00.350
and see something and see that's it beautiful
and pick it up. You're not gonna walk into

00:24:00.350 --> 00:24:05.340
a store and go, "What's organic here?" You're
not gonna do that. So you still have to inspire.

00:24:05.340 --> 00:24:08.210
You still have to create beautiful garment.

00:24:08.210 --> 00:24:14.770
So personally for us it was great because
we suddenly got access to the right kind of

00:24:14.770 --> 00:24:20.610
ethical designers who came to us 'cause they
got it. They got that this was about expression

00:24:20.610 --> 00:24:25.720
and we had to sort of uphold that and the
rest is a given. I mean to me it should be

00:24:25.720 --> 00:24:32.360
a given. Like sustainability as far as production
goes and ethical practices go, it should be

00:24:32.360 --> 00:24:37.460
a given. Like you have to be responsible in
the way you produce and create things.

00:24:37.460 --> 00:24:43.200
So now we're actually building something based
on that with these designers. We're in the

00:24:43.200 --> 00:24:46.751
process of creating a platform for ethical
designers which is in the works so that's

00:24:46.751 --> 00:24:47.751
 -- I don't know if that really answers your
question. Okay.

00:24:47.751 --> 00:24:48.751
Cool.

00:24:48.751 --> 00:24:52.200
&gt;&gt;female #3: Would it work for you?

00:24:52.200 --> 00:25:00.169
&gt;&gt;Sheena Matheiken: Well I think you have
to look at it from two sides. I was out to

00:25:00.169 --> 00:25:04.400
make a point. It's an extreme. Obviously no
one's gonna wear the same dress for a whole

00:25:04.400 --> 00:25:08.400
year. It's a creative exercise. So there is
a certain sort of stretch of the imagination

00:25:08.400 --> 00:25:12.690
and stretch of your resources happening there.
I'm not saying that's what you should do every

00:25:12.690 --> 00:25:16.240
day. It's not a literal iteration. So that's
the one side.

00:25:16.240 --> 00:25:22.460
And the other side is I mean I'm down to my
basics again. Everything that came into my

00:25:22.460 --> 00:25:27.000
wardrobe is gone because they were all donated
accessories and to be really honest with you

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:32.200
I don't have that many clothes. I don't think
about it. I actually don't think about dressing

00:25:32.200 --> 00:25:34.159
up a lot at all.

00:25:34.159 --> 00:25:38.190
I get up. It's like literally, "What am I
wearing today?" and I'm out. And I think that's

00:25:38.190 --> 00:25:43.070
how a lot of people are and that's sort of
 -- but it's not that I don't have fun with

00:25:43.070 --> 00:25:48.530
it. And it's really like, throughout the process
in the first year, 'cause I did still have

00:25:48.530 --> 00:25:53.110
my full time job, it was very important for
me to keep that daily routine spontaneous

00:25:53.110 --> 00:25:58.169
so I didn't plan ahead accept for the crazy
days like Halloween and the Mermaid Parade

00:25:58.169 --> 00:25:59.860
and things like that when I got crazy.

00:25:59.860 --> 00:26:04.429
But for the most part, it was deliberately
kept spontaneous, excuse me, because that's

00:26:04.429 --> 00:26:09.140
how most people get ready in the morning.
And I think there's a lot -- there were -- very

00:26:09.140 --> 00:26:14.809
often I would get stumped and I would just
sort work with something that I never thought

00:26:14.809 --> 00:26:18.870
I would use in that way and it would end up
working. So I think there's a lot you can

00:26:18.870 --> 00:26:22.990
stretch given the few accessories that you
do have.

00:26:22.990 --> 00:26:26.419
And I think that's actually a really interesting
point because now we're doing it for one month

00:26:26.419 --> 00:26:32.900
and you can see how the women do it differently,
but they have limited -- most of them don't

00:26:32.900 --> 00:26:37.390
go out and buy a lot of new stuff just for
that month. You're kind of working with what's

00:26:37.390 --> 00:26:38.860
in your wardrobe a lot so.

